05:07.080 --> 05:11.280
Fiction Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

06:02.160 --> 06:06.020
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:21.740 --> 06:27.040
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:29.680 --> 06:31.360
And here are your hosts.

06:35.880 --> 06:36.960
This is Daryl Lane.

06:37.000 --> 06:37.620
And Bill Vernon.

06:38.120 --> 06:42.540
Charles Sheffield's popular and provocative 1979 novel, The Web Between the Worlds, concerns

06:42.540 --> 06:43.800
a so-called space elevator.

06:44.220 --> 06:47.000
A space elevator is a satellite that is tethered to the Earth.

06:47.420 --> 06:51.000
Of course it would always remain above the same spot on the Earth's surface, or in other

06:51.000 --> 06:52.860
words, it would be in geosynchronous orbit.

06:53.340 --> 06:57.100
Sheffield has his engineers build a satellite in the tether, which is hundreds of kilometers

06:57.100 --> 06:58.460
long, out in space.

06:58.460 --> 07:02.460
The end of this beanstalk, as it's called, is then guided toward a point on the Earth's

07:02.460 --> 07:02.780
equator.

07:03.280 --> 07:05.020
A huge hole is waiting for it.

07:05.320 --> 07:09.440
As the end of the beanstalk enters the hole, millions of tons of dirt and rock are exploded

07:09.440 --> 07:11.000
over it, firmly anchoring it.

07:11.160 --> 07:15.140
Since Sheffield is a practicing physicist, he describes the whole touchy operation in

07:15.140 --> 07:16.600
believable scientific language.

07:17.160 --> 07:20.920
We ask him, though, if this method of anchoring a space elevator is a feasible one.

07:28.960 --> 07:34.380
In other words, what you've got to do is to make sure there's just enough mass at the

07:34.380 --> 07:35.640
bottom sitting there.

07:35.800 --> 07:38.540
Now, there's several ways you could propose to do that.

07:38.720 --> 07:48.540
One is to build the satellite from orbit at synchronous altitude down to the Earth, and

07:48.540 --> 07:55.280
then anchoring it is an easier job because you can put material into it a little at a

07:55.280 --> 07:55.560
time.

07:55.560 --> 07:56.900
You can bootstrap if you like.

07:57.000 --> 08:00.300
You can make a very small cable and gradually build up to a larger one.

08:00.960 --> 08:08.880
I think that the technology we will have in 100 years' time, though, is such that things

08:08.880 --> 08:14.860
we now consider hair-raising and scary and difficult, people will take for granted.

08:15.900 --> 08:20.780
To give an analogy, I like to quote, if you told people 100 years ago that there'd be

08:20.780 --> 08:26.380
hundreds of tons of metal up above the cities, they'd say, well, you could never sleep at

08:26.380 --> 08:29.360
night because you'd be afraid they'd fall on top of you all the time.

08:29.640 --> 08:33.040
But now people just curse aircraft because of the noise.

08:33.200 --> 08:36.560
They don't actually think that there's hundreds of tons of metal suspended up there.

08:37.060 --> 08:43.540
And we're not in constant fear of things collapsing because we have some trust in the

08:43.540 --> 08:44.140
technology.

08:44.640 --> 08:50.140
I believe 100 or 150 years from now, things we now consider hair-raising and scary will

08:50.140 --> 08:57.920
be commonplace, which is why I chose a more way out method of anchoring the beanstalk

08:57.920 --> 08:59.640
than the simplest one.

09:00.560 --> 09:04.220
Though the book deals with numerous scientific concepts and theories, it's an exciting

09:04.220 --> 09:06.840
fast-paced story that should please any reader of science fiction.

09:07.200 --> 09:10.500
One of the non-human characters in the book is a giant squid named Caliban.

09:10.900 --> 09:12.360
Caliban seems to be intelligent.

09:12.820 --> 09:16.480
He lives on the artificial water world of Atlantis and communicates with humans with

09:16.480 --> 09:17.260
the aid of a computer.

09:17.260 --> 09:20.900
We asked Sheffield who he got the idea of using a giant squid as a character.

09:21.580 --> 09:25.880
I needed, well, for several reasons.

09:26.020 --> 09:32.480
One is I'm very interested in cephalopods in the squid and the octopus because they are

09:32.480 --> 09:35.000
the most advanced invertebrate animals.

09:35.920 --> 09:40.560
And I had known for quite a while that squids and octopus are supposed to be very smart

09:40.560 --> 09:41.040
creatures.

09:42.040 --> 09:51.020
So when I wanted a very difficult being to communicate with, the obvious first thought

09:51.020 --> 09:54.580
which many people do is to have a computer as a character.

09:55.280 --> 10:02.080
But I felt since I had a water world in Atlantis, it would be more interesting for me to create

10:02.080 --> 10:10.640
a situation in which the sea creature, Caliban, communicates with the humans only with the

10:10.640 --> 10:11.520
help of a computer.

10:11.760 --> 10:16.680
In other words, the computer is an essential part of the communication process.

10:17.180 --> 10:22.180
And the relationship between the computer and Caliban is a very complex one that even

10:22.180 --> 10:25.480
the human characters in the book, so they don't totally know what's going on.

10:25.980 --> 10:33.080
I simply felt that was more interesting than perhaps having a computer as an instrument.

10:33.340 --> 10:39.020
A smart computer has been done quite a lot, but I felt the computer and cephalopod combination

10:39.020 --> 10:42.180
hadn't been done anywhere that I could see and was a more interesting thing to write

10:42.180 --> 10:42.520
about.

10:43.260 --> 10:45.920
We'll continue our talk with Charles Sheffield on our next show.

10:53.100 --> 10:57.420
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin Science

10:57.420 --> 11:01.640
Fiction Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

11:33.780 --> 11:36.580
Thank you.

