12:10.640 --> 12:15.740
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

12:18.600 --> 12:20.080
And here are your hosts.

12:24.360 --> 12:25.560
This is Bill Vernon.

12:25.840 --> 12:26.400
And Daryl Lane.

12:26.560 --> 12:31.060
Charles Sheffield's most recent science fiction novel, published in 1982, is entitled My

12:31.060 --> 12:33.920
Brother's Keeper, and it's a departure from his normal style.

12:34.240 --> 12:37.940
It's a fast-paced book, as all of Sheffield's works are, but it's set in the very near

12:37.940 --> 12:39.460
future and it reads like a spy novel.

12:39.800 --> 12:40.820
Sheffield talks about it.

13:16.900 --> 13:22.880
The Science Fiction aspects of the story concerns introsomatic chips, tiny microcomputer devices

13:22.880 --> 13:26.820
which are implanted in the human body to control various physiological functions.

13:27.480 --> 13:30.540
Twin brothers named Leo and Lionel are the main characters in the story.

13:30.960 --> 13:34.720
Leo leads an exciting life of intrigue and danger as a government agent involved with

13:34.720 --> 13:35.720
the introsomatic chips.

13:35.720 --> 13:40.220
And Lionel is a conservative man who is a world-renowned concert pianist, hard of the

13:40.220 --> 13:41.180
adventuresome type.

13:42.000 --> 13:44.980
After a helicopter accident involving the two brothers, Leo is dying.

13:45.480 --> 13:49.120
He is saved, in a sense, by a brilliant doctor or scientist who removes part of his brain

13:49.120 --> 13:50.380
and attaches it to Lionel's.

13:50.400 --> 13:54.600
Their personalities are sort of integrated then, and they slowly become one new person.

13:55.360 --> 13:59.460
What had been happening through the book is that it begins.

13:59.920 --> 14:04.900
Lionel, although he is the one with the consciousness, he's the one who thinks he knows who he is,

14:04.900 --> 14:10.240
when they recover consciousness, has always been the subordinate partner.

14:10.880 --> 14:15.520
His brother Leo had always been the stronger personality, the more outgoing one, and really

14:15.520 --> 14:16.340
the dominant one.

14:16.960 --> 14:23.180
Now through the book, Lionel is gradually taking on more of his brother's characteristics.

14:24.140 --> 14:30.200
And certainly at the beginning of the book, Lionel would never have dreamed of going off

14:30.200 --> 14:33.200
and chasing danger because it wasn't his disposition.

14:33.200 --> 14:39.480
So that by the end, they have somewhat fused in personality to the point where it's Leo

14:40.040 --> 14:47.360
who is really driving them along to go out and go after the criminals for the same reason

14:47.360 --> 14:51.740
he had always done it, which is that it was the best form of excitement.

14:52.120 --> 14:57.260
He got excitement from it, and he said at the end that there's really no thrill like it,

14:57.280 --> 14:58.820
which is this type of chase.

14:58.820 --> 15:02.920
But that in a sense is Leo's personality speaking by that point.

15:03.860 --> 15:10.520
Lionel was the somewhat quiet and retiring twin, but by the end of the book,

15:11.800 --> 15:16.320
it's no longer Lionel who is making most of the decisions.

15:16.680 --> 15:20.380
Leo has again become the dominant twin in a psychological sense.

15:20.500 --> 15:22.140
That's the thing I had in mind.

15:30.540 --> 15:34.120
The brain operation which joins the two brothers is not feasible presently,

15:34.340 --> 15:37.340
but Sheffield says it may not be too long before the technique becomes possible.

15:37.600 --> 15:42.560
This is a typical Sheffield story and then it's based on techniques or devices that are just over the horizon

15:42.560 --> 15:44.940
that may be possible in a decade or two.

15:45.300 --> 15:47.880
Right. Sheffield is a convincing extrapolator too,

15:48.080 --> 15:51.340
because he is a practicing scientist with a PhD in theoretical physics.

15:51.720 --> 15:55.200
We ask Sheffield if he writes his stories to seriously examine such concepts,

15:55.520 --> 15:57.280
or if he's just playing around with wild ideas.

15:57.280 --> 16:00.320
It depends on the story.

16:00.920 --> 16:10.340
If I believe that the device is technologically possible and that someday we will have it,

16:10.860 --> 16:14.420
then I try to develop the consequences of that rather seriously.

16:15.020 --> 16:20.540
And in a sense I'm attempting prediction as opposed to writing entertainment.

16:21.120 --> 16:26.360
But on the other hand, if I don't really believe something is likely to happen at all,

16:26.360 --> 16:29.200
then I'm writing for the fun of it.

16:29.320 --> 16:32.680
I'm writing and don't expect to be taken seriously.

16:33.380 --> 16:36.560
We'll continue our conversation with Charles Sheffield on our next show.

