This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

18:11.480 --> 18:13.020
And here are your hosts.

18:17.500 --> 18:18.720
This is Daryl Lane.

18:18.840 --> 18:19.440
And Bill Vernon.

18:19.840 --> 18:23.120
One of the more fascinating collections of fantasy stories to come out in recent years

18:23.120 --> 18:26.040
is Charles Sheffield's 1982 book, Erasmus Magister.

18:26.320 --> 18:30.240
Sheffield is a scientist and he's noted as an author of hard science fiction stories,

18:30.640 --> 18:35.920
but he also writes in various styles and on unexpected subjects, as Erasmus Magister demonstrates.

18:36.360 --> 18:39.960
The title refers to the main character in all of the book's stories, Erasmus Darwin,

18:40.560 --> 18:43.460
who lived in England's 18th century and was the grandfather of Charles Darwin.

18:43.700 --> 18:46.460
We asked Sheffield if Erasmus was a real historical figure.

18:47.300 --> 18:50.400
Yes, I've been interested in him for a long time.

18:51.120 --> 18:57.460
As somebody I found much more fascinating as a personality than his grandson Charles Darwin.

18:58.120 --> 19:03.400
Erasmus Darwin I had known about since I first went to Cambridge,

19:03.660 --> 19:07.120
because he attended the same college at Cambridge as I did,

19:07.540 --> 19:10.860
and there were books about him in the library and so on.

19:11.220 --> 19:13.580
And so I have an early fascination with him.

19:13.860 --> 19:17.860
And I found him especially interesting because he did so many different things.

19:18.620 --> 19:25.500
And was a poet and a philosopher and an inventor and a famous physician.

19:25.700 --> 19:27.500
And he used just a fascinating combination.

19:28.820 --> 19:36.700
I decided that what I would try to do would be to have him apply his powers of observation,

19:37.040 --> 19:40.720
which were famous throughout Europe in his day.

19:40.720 --> 19:48.060
He was noted for being able to diagnose diseases by looking at people and observing them closely.

19:48.620 --> 19:54.340
I decided that that power of observation would serve him well if he had to solve other mysteries.

19:55.340 --> 19:58.160
He was also a person who was strongly rationalistic.

19:58.280 --> 20:00.300
He didn't believe in supernatural explanations.

20:00.920 --> 20:07.400
So I decided there that it would be logical for him, through his powers of observation and deduction,

20:07.400 --> 20:14.820
to seek and find rational explanations to things that everyone else in the story thought were supernatural,

20:15.120 --> 20:16.100
which was very reasonable.

20:16.260 --> 20:20.820
200 years ago, people were very ready to believe supernatural answers to most things.

20:21.240 --> 20:24.580
So that was the logic behind the stories.

20:25.080 --> 20:26.500
There are three stories in the volume.

20:26.860 --> 20:30.220
The Devil of Malcourc, the Treasure of Odorex, and the Lambeth of Mortal.

20:30.640 --> 20:34.280
And they're extremely difficult to categorize. Sheffield talks about them.

20:34.280 --> 20:40.340
They were published in different places, and it's an interesting point.

20:40.860 --> 20:45.000
The first one was published as a fantasy in Fantastic Stories.

20:46.540 --> 20:51.060
The second one was published in Alfred Hitchcock's Mystery Magazine.

20:52.740 --> 21:00.300
And the third one, in Time, I'm talking now, in Data Publication, was published in Fantasy and Science Fiction.

21:01.020 --> 21:06.720
Now, in practice, the Devil of Malcourc was the last one written.

21:06.940 --> 21:11.960
That's the first one in the Erasers' Magister, but I wrote that last.

21:12.420 --> 21:19.580
But I was not quite sure when I was writing them, whether I was writing science fiction or fantasy,

21:19.980 --> 21:22.180
or some type of historical detective.

21:22.860 --> 21:25.940
And I finally decided it really didn't make any difference.

21:25.940 --> 21:30.820
I was trying to tell a story about what I consider to be a very interesting real person,

21:31.440 --> 21:35.680
and I tried to get the facts about Erasmus Darwin accurate,

21:35.920 --> 21:41.660
so that I was not doing any distortion to his beliefs and views or life history.

21:41.920 --> 21:47.000
But I permitted myself license when it came to the things that happened to him.

21:47.620 --> 21:51.300
So it was interesting. It was a very interesting set of stories to write.

21:51.720 --> 21:54.000
Sort of very difficult to write. I don't know why.

21:54.000 --> 21:59.000
Perhaps because I was trying to put myself back in the 18th century framework.

21:59.920 --> 22:03.100
In each story, there is an apparently supernatural happening or creature

22:03.100 --> 22:05.060
that puzzles or bedevils some part of England.

22:05.520 --> 22:09.960
The first story, the Devil of Malcourc, for instance, deals with what we today call a Loch Ness Monster.

22:10.340 --> 22:13.380
The stories are delightful reading. They're exciting, highly literate,

22:13.600 --> 22:17.160
and convincingly communicate the atmosphere of the 18th century English countryside.

22:17.660 --> 22:20.320
A reader of science fiction will find them to be different fare, certainly,

22:20.640 --> 22:22.820
but all the more enjoyable and refreshing because they are.

22:22.820 --> 22:27.220
Sheffield says there will be more Erasmus Darwin stories too, so keep an eye out for them.

22:27.460 --> 22:30.340
We'll finish our conversation with Charles Sheffield on our next show.

